      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Have and Have Not</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert S Corya letter on excessive houses in the Hamptons, and the rich who chase in vain for happiness (s)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Of course there will be readers of ''Wowing Them With Excess in the Hamptons'' (front page, July 18) who will say that these very expensive houses assault the earth's finite resources, using excess wood, gas, electricity and so on.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Of course there will be readers of ''Wowing Them With Excess in the Hamptons'' (front page, July 18) who will say that these very expensive houses assault the earth's finite resources, using excess wood, gas, electricity and so on.</p>
        <p>Some will say these houses are an insult to less fortunate peoples and nations (for example, ''Before Manila's Garbage Hill Collapsed: Living Off Scavenging,'' news article, July 18).</p>
        <p>Others will call these houses monuments to overblown egos. Some might call them examples of chasing in vain for happiness.</p>
        <p>And of course all the above are correct.</p>
        <p>ROBERT S. CORYA  Indianapolis, July 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
